  "prompt": "Are there specific laws targeting money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are specific laws targeting money laundering in many countries. In the United States, key anti-money laundering (AML) laws include:\n\n1. Bank Secrecy Act (1970)\n- Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandates record-keeping and reporting requirements\n\n2. Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- Criminalized money laundering as a federal offense\n- Established penalties for individuals and organizations\n\n3. USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced AML regulations\n- Strengthened reporting and monitoring requirements\n- Increased international cooperation\n\n4. Anti-Money Laundering Act (2020)\n- Modernized AML regulations\n- Expanded reporting requirements\n- Increased penalties for violations\n\nInternationally, organizations like:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- International Monetary Fund (IMF)\n- United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime (UNODC)\n\nWork to develop and enforce global anti-money laundering standards.\n\nThese laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income and to detect and prosecute financial crimes.",
